english:
  title: A Second Memorial
  author: Park Sang-chung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A small nation must cultivate its relationship with a great one to escape blame and punishment—this is the proper way. Yet there are four grave offenses that cannot be overlooked, and even I, in my humble ignorance, perceive them. How could those in high office claim not to see them?

    But when fear of censure clouds the mind and obscures righteousness, men will commit any wrong to avoid calamity. With such blindness, even superior wisdom becomes inferior to the simplest honesty. Allow me to name these four transgressions and propose the way to avert their consequences.

    To yield with grace and cultivate Ming was the will of the late King. Yet on the very day he passed from this world, rebellion against the North was proclaimed. As subjects serving our lord and father, we have broken faith, bringing shame upon our sovereign before the great power above. This is the first offense.

    When Wu Jinan commanded the northern garrison, he slew the people of Dingliao without authority and spread false rumors to terrify the troops. Rather than face his crime, he shielded the wrongdoer and harbored the corrupt, drawing calamity upon the realm. This is the second offense.

    Kim Ui murdered the envoy and seized the tribute horses to raise rebellion—a crime so grave that all desire his death. Yet when those who conspired with him arrived, no inquiry was made. Their guilt spreads to imperil the state itself, and we have grown callous even to the ruin of our temples and the decimation of our people. This is the third offense.

    More than a month has passed since Kim Ui's betrayal, yet no report reaches the court. When Choi Won departed, we dared defy the royal command and prevented him from crossing the border, delaying month upon month while the great power's suspicion deepens. This is the fourth offense.

    Any single one of these four sins merits destruction. How can we bear all four and still refuse justice? How can we embrace shared ruin?

    If Your Highness would but confer with the loyal and upright ministers to examine these matters clearly, guilt would find its proper place. Once the guilty are identified and detained, let the ministers present a memorial to the Emperor himself for his judgment. Can even the wisest sovereign fail to discern the truth?

    The fate of our ancestral shrines and our people hangs upon this single moment. Lose this chance, and regret shall be forever beyond remedy.
  footnotes:
    - The 'four grave offenses' refer to specific political failures during the reign of Sejo of Joseon, likely concerning diplomatic and military mishandlings that weakened the kingdom's position relative to Ming China.
    - Wu Jinan (吳季南) refers to a historical military commander whose unauthorized actions at Dingliao are presented as a grave breach of royal authority.
    - Kim Ui's rebellion and the subsequent mishandling of it forms the central political crisis that this memorial addresses.
    - The invocation of the Emperor's wisdom and moral authority reflects the tributary relationship between Joseon and Ming China during this period.
